\pard\plain \s4\qj \f16 {Zombie\par 
}\pard\plain \qj \f16\fs20 \tab Zombies created by necromancy are, like animated corpses, the fleshy remains of humanoids animated by {magick}ally-bound spirits, but a zombie\rquote s animating spirit is permanently bound to the deceased\rquote 
s remains, and has a limited self-awareness, permitting the zombie to use some of the instincts, skills, and abilities the spirit had in life.\par 
\tab Unlike skeletons and animated corpses, zombies are capable of long service if properly cared for.{ }A Zombie tends to deteriorate from decomposition and wear according to its environment and level of activity.{ }
If not subjected to regular use, and protected from the elements, a zombie\rquote s body may function acceptably for several decades.{ }If used for hard labor, or exposed to rough treatment or combat, the body may last no more than a few weeks.\par 
\tab A zombie behaves like a sleep-walking or hypnotized individual.{ }It follows its master\rquote s commands, but ignores other speakers and is only dimly aware of events in its environment.{ }
It will not, for instance, notice the threat of an attacking weapon until it is struck, and then only shambles slowly away from an attacker.\par 
\tab A zombie has access to only a fragment of the knowledge and skills it had in life.{ }A zombie can follow simple directions at its master\rquote s request, but cannot answer its master\rquote 
s questions, nor can it perform even the simplest feats of reasoning.\par 
\tab A zombie is capable of vigorous activity for no more than 3d6+9 rounds at a time, after which it must rest for about an hour to restore its aethyrial energy.{ }It is capable of moderate exercise (e.g.
, walking, light labor) for periods up to one hour.\par 
\tab A zombie may not be slain without {magick}ally severing the body\rquote s link with its spirit.{ }Even if chopped up into tiny bits, a zombie\rquote s spirit remains linked to those bits, and may continue to animate the tiny bits.{ }
Scattering the fragments of a dismembered zombie will eventually disassociate the spirit from the remote parts, while the spirit becomes associated with a particular fragment, continuing to animate that part even in the absence of the rest of the body.{ }
For example, the spirit typically remains associated with the heart or head of the zombie, though accounts of severed but animated zombie hands are not unusual.{ }
Even cremation reducing bodily remains to ash does not release the bound spirit from the ash.{ }As such, reducing Wound points to zero for a zombie does not represent killing or destroying it, but represents physically damaging the struct
ure enough that it no longer presents a threat.\par 
