They follow their master\rquote s commands like a zombie, but exercise some initiative in accomplishing tasks.{ }For instance, they instinctively defend themselves from harm (i.e.
, parry attacks, and maneuver for advantage in combat), and learn from experience.{ }They also instinctively fear injury, and as such may choose to withdraw against greater odds, unlike most undead.{ }
However, they do not have higher mental functions, communicate very crudely, if at all, and typically suffer from dementia and, when threatened or terrified, from catatonia (see {\ul WFRP}, p. 84).{ }
As such, they may make satisfactory servants, slaves, or laborers for certain simple tasks, but are less effective as guards or troops.\par 
